I read one paragraph of this write-up. It is nice and I am sure s=
elf-inquiry is a very valid path.

However I have a small but crucial disag=
reement.

<<No, God will never appear before us. As we have seen in self-re=
alisation, we have to realise the Brahmam by destroying maya.=C2=A0>>


Thi=
s is not mandatory at all. Infact God can very well appear before a seeker =
in a multitude of forms and sometimes in a form that is seemingly infinite.=
 Again God can come to a seeker not as a form but as a Light. Etc. Many pos=
sibilities. That is why it is called God. He/She/it is beyond ALL limits, y=
et it rejects no option, that humans may impose on it through their minds o=
r their experiences, spiritual or otherwise.

This thing called God is best=
 described by one adjective - Infinite. And the basic character of Infinity=
 is that it can't be totally understood by anyone. You can only understand =
some parts of it, every the entirety. Being Infinite, it is beyond restrict=
ions. So it is both with form and without form. And at times even simultane=
ously. [Sounds illogical no? But Infinity was anyway, even in mathematics, =
never within the purview of normal logic.]

It is only the limitations of t=
he seeker which limits the experience of God in all its totality. He/She/It=
 is the sum total of all that is imaginable, all that is difficult to imagi=
ne and all that just cannot be humanly imagined. Forms, therefore, get incl=
uded inside it.

Of forms again there are various characteristics. Not all =
forms are similar. The same devata can appear in two different nature of fo=
rm depending on the seeker, one maybe more sutble than the other.

Basicall=
y noting every single possibility makes it tremendously complicated, but bo=
ttomline is that God is both with form and also without form. And one is no=
t necessarily higher than the other aspect of God.

That's my view. Feel fr=
ee to disagree. No imposition.

